**2. Wire it up in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Adds ProblemDetails support for automatic RFC 7807 responses
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();
// Register your custom handler
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<CustomExceptionHandler>();

var app = builder.Build();

// Must be registered early in the pipeline
app.UseExceptionHandler();

// Your endpoints below...
app.MapGet("/items/{id}", (int id) =>
{
    throw new KeyNotFoundException($"Item {id} not found.");
});

app.Run();
```

**How it works:**

| Exception | Status | Detail |
|-----------|--------|--------|
| `KeyNotFoundException` | 404 | Exception message |
| `ArgumentException` | 400 | Exception message |
| `InvalidOperationException` | 409 | Exception message |
| Anything else | 500 | Generic message (no leak) |

**Key points:**

- `IExceptionHandler` (available since .NET 8) catches all unhandled exceptions globally — no per-endpoint try-catch needed.
- For 500s, `exception.Message` is suppressed to avoid leaking internals.
- The response `Content-Type` is automatically `application/problem+json`.
- You can register multiple `IExceptionHandler` implementations; they run in order until one returns `true`.
